\begin_layout Itemize
Approximate spiking model by simple rate models 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The derived models are described by low-dimensional ordinary differential
 equations (ODEs) which depend on a number of quantities defined in the
 
\series bold
plane
\series default
 of generic input mean and standard deviation 
\begin_inset Formula $(\mu,\sigma)$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Steady spike rate as a function of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
r_{\infty}(\mu,\sigma)\coloneqq\lim_{t\rightarrow\infty}r(t;\mu_{\text{tot}=\mu},\sigma_{\text{tot}}=\sigma)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
When simulating the reduced models these quantities need to be evaluated
 for each discrete time point 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 at a certain value 
\begin_inset Formula $(\mu,\sigma)$
\end_inset

 which depends on the overall synaptic moments 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu_{\text{syn}}(t)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{\text{syn}}^{2}(t)$
\end_inset

 and on the mean adaptation current 
\begin_inset Formula $\bigl\langle w\bigr\rangle(t)$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Quantities depend on the parameters of the synaptic input and adaption current
 only through their arguments 
\begin_inset Formula $(\mu,\sigma)$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Therefore, for given parameter values of the EIF model 
\begin_inset Formula $(C,g_{L},E_{L},\Delta_{T},V_{T},V_{r},T_{\text{ref}})$
\end_inset

 the authors precalculate those quantities on a reasonably large and sufficientl
y dense grid of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma$
\end_inset

 values, and access them during time integration by interpolating the quantity
 values 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The derived low-dimensional models describe the spike rate dynamics and
 generally do 
\series bold
not
\series default
 express the evolution of the entire membrane voltage distribution 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Therefore, the mean adaptation dynamics which depend on the density 
\begin_inset Formula $p(V,t)$
\end_inset

 via 
\begin_inset Formula $\bigl\langle V\bigr\rangle$
\end_inset

 is adjusted through approximating the mean membrane voltage 
\begin_inset Formula $\bigl\langle V\bigr\rangle$
\end_inset

 by the expectation over steady-state 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\bigl\langle V\bigr\rangle=\frac{\int_{-\infty}^{V_{s}}vp_{\infty}(v)dv}{\int_{-\infty}^{V_{s}}p_{\infty}(v)dv}
\]

\end_inset

which is valid for sufficiently slow adaptation current dynamics 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
Spectral models 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
We can specify Fokker-Planck 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{\partial p}{\partial t}=\mathcal{L}(\mu_{\text{tot}}(t),\sigma_{\text{tot}}(t))[p]
\]

\end_inset

which depends on the 
\series bold
time-varying
\series default
 total input moments 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu_{\text{tot}}(t,r_{d},\bigl\langle w\bigr\rangle)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{\text{tot}}^{2}(t,r_{d})$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
For each value of 
\begin_inset Formula $(\mu,\sigma)$
\end_inset

 the operator 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}$
\end_inset

possesses an infinite, discrete set of eigenvalues 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{n}$
\end_inset

 in the left complex half-plane and associated eigenfunctions 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathcal{L}[\phi_{n}]=\lambda_{n}\phi_{n}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Boundary conditions need to be fulfilled for each eigenfunctions 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{n}$
\end_inset

 separately 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Reset boundary condition 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
q_{\phi_{n}}(V_{r}^{+})-q_{\phi_{n}}(V_{r}^{-})=q_{\phi_{n}}(V_{s})
\]

\end_inset

where we neglected the refractory period, i.e.
 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{\text{ref}}=0$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Incorporating the refractory period is straightforward 
\series bold
only 
\series default
for the time independent 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu_{\text{tot}}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{\text{tot}}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Adjoint eigenfunctions 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathcal{L}^{*}[\psi_{n}]=\lambda_{n}\psi_{n}
\]

\end_inset

need need to satisfy three boundary conditions 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\psi_{n}(V_{s}) & =\psi_{n}(V_{r})\\
\frac{\partial\psi_{n}(V_{\text{lb}})}{\partial V} & =0\\
\frac{\partial\psi_{n}(V_{\text{r}}^{+})}{\partial V} & =\frac{\partial\psi_{n}(V_{\text{r}}^{-})}{\partial V}
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\begin_inset Note Note
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Proof
\begin_inset Note Note
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
What does change when the left boundary is not at minus infinity but instead
 a relfecting boundary at 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{\text{lb}}$
\end_inset

.
 Reflecting boundary requires that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
q_{\phi}(V_{\text{lb}})=0
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
We start from 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
(\psi,L\phi)=-\int_{V_{\text{lb}}}^{V_{\text{th}}}dV\,\psi\partial_{V}q_{\phi}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Partial integration yields 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
(\psi,L\phi)=-\left.\psi q_{\phi}\right|_{V_{\text{lb}}}^{V_{\text{th}}}+\int_{V_{\text{lb}}}^{V_{\text{th}}}\partial_{V}\psi q_{\phi}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
The flux at the left boundary 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{\phi}(V_{\text{lb}})=0$
\end_inset

 is zero, hence 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
(\psi,L\phi)=-\psi(V_{\text{th}})q_{\phi}(V_{\text{th}})+\int_{V_{\text{lb}}}^{V_{\text{th}}}(\partial_{V}\psi)q_{\phi}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
The integral is given by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\int_{V_{\text{lb}}}^{V_{\text{th}}}(\partial_{V}\psi)q_{\phi} & =\int_{V_{\text{lb}}}^{V_{\text{th}}}(\partial_{V}\psi)(a(V)-b\partial_{V})\phi\\
 & =\int_{V_{\text{lb}}}^{V_{\text{th}}}(\partial_{V}\psi)a(V)\phi-b\int_{V_{\text{lb}}}^{V_{\text{th}}}(\partial_{V}\psi)\partial_{V}\phi
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Partial integration for the second integral yields 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\int_{V_{\text{lb}}}^{V_{\text{th}}}(\partial_{V}\psi)\partial_{V}\phi=\left.(\partial_{V}\psi)\phi\right|_{V_{\text{lb}}}^{V_{\text{th}}}-\int_{V_{\text{lb}}}^{V_{\text{th}}}(\partial_{V}^{2}\psi)\phi
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Using 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi(V_{\text{th}})=0$
\end_inset

 yields 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\int_{V_{\text{lb}}}^{V_{\text{th}}}(\partial_{V}\psi)\partial_{V}\phi=-\psi'(V_{\text{lb}})\phi(V_{\text{lb}})-\int_{V_{\text{lb}}}^{V_{\text{th}}}(\partial_{V}^{2}\psi)\phi
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
We arrive at 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
(\psi,L\phi)=-\psi(V_{\text{th}})q_{\phi}(V_{\text{th}})+\psi'(V_{\text{lb}})\phi(V_{\text{lb}})+\int_{V_{\text{lb}}}^{V_{\text{th}}}\left\{ a(V)(\partial_{V}\psi)+b(\partial_{V}^{2}\psi)\right\} \phi
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Hence, we find 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathcal{L^{\dagger}}=a(V)\partial_{V}+b\partial_{V}^{2}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Choose boundary conditions 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\psi'(V_{\text{lb}})=0
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
What are we doing with 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
-\psi(V_{\text{th}})q_{\phi}(V_{\text{th}})=?
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Split integral at the reset 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
(\psi,L\phi) & =-\int_{V_{\text{lb}}}^{V_{\text{th}}}dV\,\psi\partial_{V}q_{\phi}\\
 & =-\int_{V_{\text{lb}}}^{V_{\text{r}}^{-}}dV\,\psi\partial_{V}q_{\phi}-\int_{V_{\text{r}}^{+}}^{V_{\text{th}}}dV\,\psi\partial_{V}q_{\phi}
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
We have 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
-\int_{a}^{b}dV\,\psi\partial_{V}q_{\phi}=\left.-\psi q_{\phi}\right|_{a}^{b}+\int_{a}^{b}dV\,(\partial_{V}\psi)q_{\phi}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Boundary terms 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
-\left\{ \left.\psi q_{\phi}\right|_{V_{\text{lb}}}^{V_{\text{r}}^{-}}+\left.\psi q_{\phi}\right|_{V_{\text{r}}^{+}}^{V_{\text{th}}}\right\}  & =-\left\{ \psi(V_{\text{r}}^{-})q_{\phi}(V_{\text{r}}^{-})+\psi(V_{\text{th}})q_{\phi}(V_{\text{th}})-\psi(V_{\text{r}}^{+})q_{\phi}(V_{\text{r}}^{+})\right\} \\
 & =\psi(V_{\text{r}}^{+})q_{\phi}(V_{\text{r}}^{+})-\psi(V_{\text{r}}^{-})q_{\phi}(V_{\text{r}}^{-})-\psi(V_{\text{th}})q_{\phi}(V_{\text{th}})
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
We have 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
q_{\phi}(V_{\text{r}}^{+})-q_{\phi}(V_{\text{r}}^{-})=q_{\phi}(V_{\text{th}})
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Hence, choosing 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\psi(V_{\text{r}})=\psi(V_{\text{th}})
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
makes the boundary term vanish.
 We continue with 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\int_{a}^{b}dV\,(\partial_{V}\psi)q_{\phi}=
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Last condition ensures continuous derivative of 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi_{n}$
\end_inset

 at 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{r}$
\end_inset

 in contrast to the eigenfunctions 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{n}$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}$
\end_inset

 that have a kink at the reset due to reinjection condition
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Expand onto 
\series bold
moving 
\series default
eigenbasis of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
p(V,t)=\sum_{n=0}^{\infty}\alpha_{n}(t)\phi_{n}(V)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Infinite dimensional equation for the complex-valued projection coefficients
 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{\alpha}(t)=(\alpha_{1}(t),\alpha_{2}(t),\ldots)$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\dot{\boldsymbol{\alpha}}=(\boldsymbol{\Lambda}+\boldsymbol{C}_{\mu}\dot{\mu}_{\text{tot}}+\boldsymbol{C}_{\sigma^{2}}\dot{\sigma}_{\text{tot}}^{2})\boldsymbol{\alpha}+c_{\mu}\dot{\mu}{}_{\text{tot}}+\boldsymbol{c}_{\sigma^{2}}\dot{\sigma}_{\text{tot}}^{2}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
This dynamic is initialized by 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{n}(0)=\bigl\langle\psi_{n},p_{0}\bigr\rangle$
\end_inset

 and is complemented by an expression 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
r(t)=r_{\infty}+\boldsymbol{f}\cdot\boldsymbol{\alpha}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The quantities 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{\Lambda},\boldsymbol{C}_{\mu},\boldsymbol{C}_{\sigma^{2}},\boldsymbol{c}_{\mu},\boldsymbol{c}_{\sigma^{2}},r_{\infty},\boldsymbol{f},\bigl\langle V\bigr\rangle_{\infty}$
\end_inset

 all depend on time via the total input moments 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu_{\text{tot}},\sigma_{\text{tot}}^{2}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Particularly, at time 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 the biorthonormal solution of the eigenvalue problems for 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}$
\end_inset

 and its adjoint 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}^{*}$
\end_inset

 is required for 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\mu & =\mu_{\text{tot}}(t,r_{d},\bigl\langle w\bigr\rangle)\\
\sigma & =\sigma_{\text{tot}}(t,r_{d})
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Although the spectral representation is fully equivalent to the original
 Fokker-Planck equation without refractory period and while it contains
 only time derivatives it is still an infinite-dimensional and furthermore
 generally an implicit model 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Therefore, to derive an explicit low-dimensional ordinary differential model
 for the spike rate 
\begin_inset Formula $r(t)$
\end_inset

, it is not sufficient to truncate the expansion after sum finite number
 of terms but 
\series bold
additional assumptions have to be considered 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*
Numerical solver
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Start from 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathcal{L}[\phi_{n}]=\lambda_{n}\phi_{n}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
This second order differential equation can be written as 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
-\frac{d}{dV}\begin{pmatrix}q_{\phi}\\
\phi
\end{pmatrix}=\begin{pmatrix}0 & \lambda\\
\frac{2}{\sigma^{2}} & -2\frac{g(V)+\mu}{\sigma^{2}}
\end{pmatrix}\begin{pmatrix}q_{\phi}\\
\phi
\end{pmatrix}\label{eq: ev problem}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $g(V)=\frac{I_{L}(V)+I_{\text{exp}}(V)}{C}$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Note Note
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Proof 
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
We start from 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathcal{L}[\phi_{n}]=\lambda_{n}\phi_{n}
\]

\end_inset

which can be written as 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
-\frac{dq_{\phi}}{dV}=\lambda\phi
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
q_{\phi}=\left(\frac{I_{L}(V)+I_{\text{exp}}(V)}{C}+\mu(t)\right)\phi-\frac{\sigma^{2}}{2}\frac{d\phi}{dV}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Solving for 
\begin_inset Formula $d\phi/dV$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
-\frac{d\phi}{dV}=\frac{2}{\sigma^{2}}q_{\phi}-\frac{2}{\sigma^{2}}\left(\frac{I_{L}(V)+I_{\text{exp}}(V)}{C}+\mu\right)\phi
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Using 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
g(V)=\frac{I_{L}(V)+I_{\text{exp}}(V)}{C}
\]

\end_inset

we arrive at 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
-\frac{d\phi}{dV}=\frac{2}{\sigma^{2}}q_{\phi}-2\frac{g(V)+\mu}{\sigma^{2}}\phi
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Both equations can be combined into a matrix equation 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
-\frac{d}{dV}\begin{pmatrix}q_{\phi}\\
\phi
\end{pmatrix}=\begin{pmatrix}0 & \lambda\\
\frac{2}{\sigma^{2}} & -2\frac{g(V)+\mu}{\sigma^{2}}
\end{pmatrix}\begin{pmatrix}q_{\phi}\\
\phi
\end{pmatrix}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
A direct discretization, e.g.
 by a finite difference approximation of the membrane voltage derivatives
 can be applied 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Boundary conditions need to be incorporated 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Poor convergence, i.e.
 extremely small voltage steps 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta V$
\end_inset

 have to be chosen for the finite difference 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Alternative solution procedure, reformulate system with boundary conditions
 as 
\series bold
complex valued root finding problem
\series default
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\lambda\mapsto q_{\phi}(V_{\text{lb}},\lambda)=0
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Integrate Eq.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq: ev problem"

\end_inset

backward starting from the right boundary 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{s}$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi(V_{s})=0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{\phi}(V_{s})\in\mathbb{C\backslash}\{0\}$
\end_inset

 can be chosen arbitrarily 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
We integrate over the reset boundary conditions 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{\phi}(V_{r}^{-})=q_{\phi}(V_{r}^{+})-q_{\phi}(V_{s})$
\end_inset

 which introduces a discontinuity in 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{\phi}$
\end_inset

 to the lower bound 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{\text{lb}}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
There a nonzero value of 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{\phi}(V_{\text{lb}})\in\mathbb{C}$
\end_inset

 indicates that 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

 is not an eigenvalue since 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi(V)$
\end_inset

 violates the reflecting boundary condition 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $q_{\phi}(V)=0$
\end_inset

 on the other hand shows that 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

 is an eigenvalue 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Start from 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu$
\end_inset

 small enough 
\begin_inset Formula $\Rightarrow$
\end_inset

 all eigenvalues are real 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Find eigenvalues on the real line 
\begin_inset Formula $\{\lambda_{0},\lambda_{1},\ldots\}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Eigenvalues depend continuously on the input parameter 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu,\sigma$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Change 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu,\sigma^{2}$
\end_inset

 step-wise and use previous set of eigenvalues as initial guess 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Exponential integration: Start from 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
-\frac{d}{dV}\begin{pmatrix}q_{\phi}\\
\phi
\end{pmatrix}=\boldsymbol{A}(V)\begin{pmatrix}q_{\phi}\\
\phi
\end{pmatrix}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
We can not write down a formal solution because the matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{A}$
\end_inset

 depends on 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Instead, we discretize membrane voltage 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{m}=V_{\text{lb}}+m\Delta V$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $m=0,\ldots,N_{V}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{N_{V}}=V_{\text{s}}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Perform integration by steps.
 We approximate 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{A}(V)$
\end_inset

 in the interval 
\begin_inset Formula $[V_{m-1},V_{m}]$
\end_inset

 by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\boldsymbol{A}(V)\approx\boldsymbol{A}(V_{m-\frac{1}{2}})
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Next, we integrate 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
-\frac{d}{dV}\begin{pmatrix}q_{\phi}\\
\phi
\end{pmatrix}=\boldsymbol{A}(V_{m-\frac{1}{2}})\begin{pmatrix}q_{\phi}\\
\phi
\end{pmatrix}
\]

\end_inset

from 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{m-1}$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{m}$
\end_inset

 which yields 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\begin{pmatrix}q_{\phi}^{m-1}\\
\phi^{m-1}
\end{pmatrix}=\exp\left(\boldsymbol{A}(V_{m-\frac{1}{2}})\Delta V\right)\begin{pmatrix}q_{\phi}^{m}\\
\phi^{m}
\end{pmatrix}
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Note Note
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Proof 
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
We start from 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
-\frac{d}{dV}\begin{pmatrix}q_{\phi}\\
\phi
\end{pmatrix}=\boldsymbol{A}(V_{m-\frac{1}{2}})\begin{pmatrix}q_{\phi}\\
\phi
\end{pmatrix}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Substitute 
\begin_inset Formula $v(V)=V_{m}-V$
\end_inset

.
 The formal solution of the above equation is 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\begin{pmatrix}q_{\phi}\\
\phi
\end{pmatrix}=\exp(\boldsymbol{A}(V_{m-\frac{1}{2}})v)\begin{pmatrix}q_{\phi}^{m}\\
\phi^{m}
\end{pmatrix}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Assume that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\begin{pmatrix}q_{\phi}(V_{m})\\
\phi(V_{m})
\end{pmatrix}=\begin{pmatrix}q_{\phi}^{m}\\
\phi^{m}
\end{pmatrix}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
is known.
 Using 
\begin_inset Formula $v(V_{m})=0$
\end_inset

, we find 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\begin{pmatrix}c_{1}\\
c_{2}
\end{pmatrix}=\begin{pmatrix}q_{\phi}^{m}\\
\phi^{m}
\end{pmatrix}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
We can insert 
\begin_inset Formula $v(V_{m-1})=V_{m}-V_{m-1}=\Delta V$
\end_inset

 to obtain
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\begin{pmatrix}q_{\phi}^{m-1}\\
\phi^{m-1}
\end{pmatrix}=\exp(\boldsymbol{A}(V_{m-\frac{1}{2}})\Delta V)\begin{pmatrix}q_{\phi}^{m}\\
\phi^{m}
\end{pmatrix}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

